b07f014b-cee9-4171-857f-ba337f564720.2a2eaa62-432c-4f98-8ab7-57091d990837.description=
Check to see if the value stored in a specified flow variable, denoted by key, is null.

Inputs\:
keyName - The key to check, i.e. the name of the flow variable.

Returns\: 
The value in the specified key, i.e. flow variable.

Responses\:
isNull - If the key is a null pointer, i.e. the flow variable doesn't have an assigned value.
notNull - If some value is stored in the key, i.e the flow variable has a value assigned.

b07f014b-cee9-4171-857f-ba337f564720.description=
Synopsis

    This flow builds the NAS configuration for the storage product.
    doPlumbNas performs the following steps\:
      1. Set the failover group name based on the vLan ID.
      2. Check for a node input.
      3. If a node does not exist, use the flow getNodeOfVserver to retrieve the node.
      4. If a node does exist, check for a parent interface input.
      5. If the parent interface does not exist, use the flow getNumNetLifsPerPhysPortLi to retrieve the parentInterface.
      6. If the parent interface does exist, retrieve a list of vLans.
      7. Sort the list of vLans by vLan ID. If none exist on the cluster, check that the LIF exists.
      8. If vLans exist on the cluster, put the list in a xslt format, set a flag to skip the vLan create step, and check that the LIF exists.
      9. If the LIF does exist, determine whether the vLan should be created.
    10. If the LIF does not exist, retrieve a list of LIFs, put the list in a xslt format, set the flag to skip the LIF create step, and decide if the vLan should be created.
    11. Create the vLan (if applicable).
    12. Decide whether to create the LIF.
    13. Generate the LIF interface name.
    14. Create the net interface.
    15. Build the NAS net port configuration, using the flow buildSusNasFgNetPortConfig.
    16. Modify the net interface.
    17. Decide whether to configure the default gateway. Set the default gateway by IP address if configuring.
    18. Reverse the net interface.

Inputs

    clusterName - The IP or host name of the NetApp cluster (required).
      Valid values\: Dot-decimal notation IPv4 address or RFC 1123 compliant host name.
      Default value\: None.

    vServerName - The name of the vServer to be used in the flow (required).
    protocol - The protocol used in the flow (i.e. NFS, CIFS, etc) (required).
    ipAddress - The IP address of the LIF (required).
    netMask - The net mask of the IP address (required).
    vlanId - The name of the vLan used in the flow (required).
    failoverGroup - The failover group assigned to the cluster (required).
    node - The contoller node for the clusterName (required).
    parentInterface - (required). 
      Valid values\: Implementation-specific.
      Default value\: 

    port - The actual port that the LIF is assigned to.
    interfaceName - 
    defaultGateway - 
    routingGroup - 
      Valid values\: Implementation-specific.
      Default value\: 

    doLifCheck - 
      Valid values\: 
      Default value\: 

    overrideJRAS - Value to override the system defined Java RAS server.
      Valid values\: Implementation specific.
      Default value\: Hosting Eng RAS.

Results

    hpooFlowResult - The XML response specific to the functionality of the flow;  {what does this flow return and how is it returned?}  See Notes section for more details.
    flowStatus - Overall status of the flow, value is one of the string literals "success" or "failed".

Responses

    Success - All operations and subflows completed successfully.
    Failure - Some operations and/or subflows failed.

Notes

    1. Anything else the caller or support person may need to know about the flow. Relationships that aren't easily inferred, abmnormal flow behaviors, hard-codings, etc.
b07f014b-cee9-4171-857f-ba337f564720.f1f2ad55-5dad-4b08-88b0-3c1d0915432c.description=
This is an operation that does nothing, and can be used to display information to the user by editing the display tab. It can also be used for filtering flow variables by feeding them in as inputs, and filtering them on the results tab.

Inputs\:
field1 - optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
field2 - optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
field3 - optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
field4 - optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.

Responses\:
success - this operation never fails.
